[Student "S"]
{With 9 points and a 5-card Major suit you should definitely transfer, so you bid 2\H. Partner replies 2\S.  

With 9 points and a 5-card Major suit you should definitely transfer, so you bid 2\H. Partner replies 2\S. 

Now you complete the sequence by bidding 2NT, trusting partner to put it in the right place. He has maximum points and a doubleton \S so he puts it in 3NT.

The contract would be 3NT played by South.

North plays 3NT. East leads the \H6, West follows with the \H5. What will you play from dummy? And what will you play from your hand.

Winner List: \S = 0 : \H = 2 : \D = 1 : \C = 2 :: Total = 5

It's not as bad as that Winner List looks; you can establish 4 \S winners very easily.

In fact, it looks so good you might wonder what could possibly go wrong. Here's something that can go wrong. The defenders take the <b>SECOND</b> \S trick with their \SA. Can you get back to dummy for those other three winners? 

Maybe you can and maybe you can't. It depends on what you played from your hand at the first trick. If you won that trick in your hand with the \HA, then YES, you can get to dummy by leading twice toward the \H Q J.

But if you won the first trick more cheaply with your \H10, (or perhaps dummy's \HJ), and you still have that \HA in your hand then East will prevent you from ever getting to dummy.

It is ingrained in Bridge players to win tricks with the smallest card possible. And while that is usually a good idea it can sometimes be a huge mistake.

Suppose you win the first trick with your \H10. If you later play your \HA then East's \HK will stop you from getting to dummy. But if instead you play a small \H toward the \H Q J East will grab his \HK and your own \HA will block your entry.

But if you take the first trick with a "spendthrift" \HA then dummy's \H Q J will become a guaranteed entry to the \Ss.

And notice - no matter which way you play it you still end up with exactly 2 \H tricks. So the play doesn't cost a trick, it just gains an entry.}
[Play "W"]H6

