[Student "S"]
{Partner has 20 or 21 points, balanced, and you have 6. You bid 3NT, hoping partner has \D K Q x.

The contract would be 3NT played by North.

South plays 3NT. West leads the \C2 and East plays the \CJ.

Question 1: Do you hold up?

Winner List: \S = 3 : \H = 1 : \D = 1 : \C = 2 :: Total = 7

The lead of the \C2 tells you that West has only a 4-card suit, so there is no need to hold up. In fact if you did hold up East might play an unwelcome \H back.

Your best bet is going to be the \D suit, but dummy isn't exactly loaded with entries. How will you manage it? 

When entries are really scarce the best approach is ducking. Win the \CK and play a low \D from both hands. A defender will win this and probably continue with a \C. 

Stick to the plan. Win the \CA and again play small \Ds from both hands, relaxing when both defenders follow suit to the second \D.

They can now cash their 2 \Cs, and you had to give them 2 \Ds. But that's the only tricks they will get. Dummy's 3 \Ds are good and you still have a \D in your hand to get there.

When dummy has a long suit with no outside entries, always consider using a duck to make up for the lack of entries.

In this case it was a double-duck.}
[Play "W"]C2

